04763nam a22006615i 9780231508773DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20052005nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979953806  a97802315087737 a10.7312/jone134382doi  a(DE-B1597)458974  a(OCoLC)614998931  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a201/.41 aJones, Robert Alun, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Secret of the Totem :bReligion and Society from McLennan to Freud /cRobert Alun Jones. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (360 p.) :bspot art  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- t1. Totemism as Animal Worship -- t2. Totemism as Sacrament -- t3. Totemism as Utility -- t4. Totemism as Self-Transcendence -- t5. Totemism as Neurosis -- tConclusion. The Secret of the Totem -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThough it is now discredited, totemism once captured the imagination of Sigmund Freud, Émile Durkheim, James Frazer, and other prominent Victorian thinkers. In this lively intellectual history, Robert Alun Jones considers the construction of a theory and the divergent ways religious scholars, anthropologists, psychoanalysts, and cultural theorists drew on totemism to explore and define primitive and modern societies' religious, cultural, and sexual norms. Combining innovative readings of individual scholars' work and a rich portrait of Victorian intellectual life, Jones brilliantly traces the rise and fall of a powerful idea. First used to describe the belief systems of Native American tribes, totemism ultimately encompassed a range of characteristics. Its features included belief in a guardian spirit that assumed the form of an a particular animal; a prohibition against marrying outside the clan combined with a powerful incest taboo; a sacrament in which members of the totemic clan slaughtered a representative of the totemic species; and the tracing of descent through the female rather than the male. These attributes struck a chord with the late Victorian mentality and its obsession with inappropriate sexual relations, evolutionary theory, and gender roles. Totemism represented a set of beliefs that, though utterly primitive and at a great evolutionary distance, reassured Victorians of their own more civilized values and practices.Totemism's attraction to Victorian thinkers reflects the ways in which the social sciences construct their objects of study rather than discovering them. In discussing works such as Freud's Totem and Taboo or Frazer's The Golden Bough, Jones considers how theorists used the vocabulary of totemism to suit their intellectual interests and goals. Ultimately, anthropologists such as A. A. Goldenweiser, Franz Boas, and Claude Lévi-Strauss argued that totemism was more a reflection of the concerns of Victorian theorists than of the actual practices and beliefs of "primitive" societies, and by the late twentieth century totemism seemed to have disappeared altogether.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/jone1343840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231508773423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231508773/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  a